{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657804"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:37:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:37:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20680"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20680"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94529"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13556"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20680"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77569"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11784"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94529"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a temperature of 39.2\u00b0C, chills, and malaise. Blood cultures are positive for gram-negative bacteria. The clinician explains that her fever is part of the body\u0027s acute-phase response to infection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological mechanism of fever in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct bacterial toxin action on the hypothalamus","Autoantibody production against hypothalamic temperature sensors","Bacterial lipopolysaccharide stimulates release of cytokines that induce prostaglandin E2 production","Dehydration causing impaired thermoregulation","Increased metabolic rate from bacterial replication"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism is that \u003Cstrong\u003Ebacterial lipopolysaccharide stimulates release of cytokines that induce prostaglandin E2 production\u003C/strong\u003E. In bacterial infections, lipopolysaccharide (LPS) from gram-negative bacteria acts as an exogenous pyrogen that stimulates immune cells to release endogenous pyrogens, primarily interleukin-1 (IL-1) and tumor necrosis factor (TNF). These cytokines upregulate cyclooxygenase enzymes in vascular and perivascular cells of the hypothalamus, leading to increased prostaglandin E2 (PGE2) synthesis. PGE2 then acts on the hypothalamus to reset the body\u0027s temperature set point to a higher level, resulting in fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect bacterial toxin action on the hypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E - Bacterial toxins do not directly act on the hypothalamus to cause fever; rather, they stimulate the release of endogenous pyrogens from immune cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoantibody production against hypothalamic temperature sensors\u003C/strong\u003E - Fever in bacterial infections is not caused by autoimmune mechanisms targeting hypothalamic temperature sensors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDehydration causing impaired thermoregulation\u003C/strong\u003E - Although dehydration may occur during fever, it is a consequence rather than the cause of fever. Fever is an active process involving cytokines and prostaglandins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased metabolic rate from bacterial replication\u003C/strong\u003E - While bacterial infections may increase metabolic rate, this is not the primary mechanism of fever. Fever results from a reset of the hypothalamic temperature set point.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) reduce fever by inhibiting cyclooxygenase enzymes, thereby decreasing prostaglandin synthesis. This explains why medications like aspirin and ibuprofen are effective antipyretics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fever is a manifestation of the acute-phase response characterized by an elevation of body temperature by 1\u00b0C to 4\u00b0C.","Exogenous pyrogens (e.g., bacterial lipopolysaccharide) stimulate immune cells to release endogenous pyrogens (IL-1 and TNF).","Prostaglandin E2 (PGE2) acts on the hypothalamus to reset the body\u0027s temperature set point, leading to fever.","Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs reduce fever by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 101-102"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77569"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20680"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77569"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-24T12:46:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-24T12:48:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13556"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94529"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{